        body: "Wilson & Schooler (1991): one group tasted five jams and rated them. Another group tasted, articulated <em>why</em> they liked each one, then rated. The verbalisers' choices drifted away from expert ratings — they got <em>worse</em>. A follow-up: dorm-poster pickers who analysed their preferences came home with posters they later hated. <strong>Verbal overshadowing.</strong> Chapter 12's \"the five colours blind the eye\" is also \"the labels ruin the meal.\"",
